<H1>How To Publish an RFC</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<HR>

<P>
<H2>RFCs from the IETF</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Before the RFC Editor considers publication of a document, =
it must=20
  first be published as an <A=20
  href=3D"ftp://ftp.ietf.org/ietf/1id-guidelines.txt">Internet Draft</A> =
(I-D).=20
  All RFCs have been I-Ds, but not all I-Ds become RFCs. I-D authors =
should read=20
  <A href=3D"ftp://ftp.isi.edu/in-notes/rfc2223.txt">RFC 2223</A> =
"Instructions to=20
  Authors" before they submit their document as an I-D so that it may be =

  formatted correctly for future RFC submission.=20
  <P>RFCs that originate within the IETF process will already be I-Ds, =
and they=20
  reach the RFC Editor through the IESG. Members of the IESG include the =
IETF=20
  Area Directors (ADs), who are responsible sets of related working =
groups.=20
  These working groups develop documents that may be approved for =
publication as=20
  RFCs by the ADs. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Independent Submissions</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>In addition, anyone can write an RFC and independently =
submit it=20
  to the RFC Editor for possible publication, but the author must first =
publish=20
  the document as an Internet Draft. This gives the IETF community and =
the IESG=20
  a chance to read and comment upon the document and to give the RFC =
Editor=20
  advice on its suitability for publication.=20
  <P>Once an independent submission has been posted as an I-D, the =
author may=20
  send e-mail to <A=20
  =
href=3D"mailto:rfc-editor@rfc-editor.org">rfc-editor@rfc-editor.org</A> =
saying=20
  that you would like the document to be considered as an Informational =
or=20
  Experimental RFC (please specify).=20
  <P>The RFC Editor will request for the IESG to review the document and =
give=20
  comments/suggestions about publication.=20
  <P>If the IESG recommends against publication, the author(s) will be =
CC'd on=20
  the email so they may know the reasons. Sometimes documents submitted=20
  individually are remanded to an IETF Working Group that is already =
working on=20
  the same subject; in these cases the author is asked to work with the =
IETF to=20
  develop the document. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Tracking the Publication Process</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>RFCs in the publication process can be tracked by looking at =
the=20
  <A href=3D"http://www.rfc-editor.org/queue.html">RFC Queue</A>. =
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Final Review Period</H2>
<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Once an RFC has been edited and is ready for publication,=20
  author(s) are given 48 hours to look over their document for editorial =
nits.=20
  We STRONGLY suggest that authors check for spelling and missing words =
and that=20
  they make sure the references, contact information are up to date. =
Also, if=20
  your document is a MIB we encourage you to take one last look at your =
CODE. We=20
  DO NOT make changes to RFCs once they have been published, so please =
look over=20
  your document carefully.=20
  <P>Upon request of an author, we will extend the 48 hours a reasonable =
amount.=20
  </P></BLOCKQUOTE>
